{
  "What is the quadratic formula?": "",
  "x = (−b ± √(b² − 4ac)) / (2a)": "",
  "When does the quadratic formula work?": "",
  "Always — it solves any quadratic equation ax² + bx + c = 0": "",
  "What does ± mean in the formula?": "",
  "There are potentially two solutions (one with + and one with −)": "",
  "For x² + 5x + 6 = 0, identify a, b, c.": "",
  "a = 1, b = 5, c = 6": "",
  "Solve: x² − 3x + 2 = 0": "",
  "x = (3 ± √(9−8))/2 = (3 ± 1)/2 → x = 2 or x = 1": "",
  "Solve: x² + 2x − 15 = 0": "",
  "x = (−2 ± √(4+60))/2 = (−2 ± 8)/2 → x = 3 or x = −5": "",
  "Why is the quadratic formula always reliable?": "",
  "It works even when factoring is difficult or impossible": "",
  "Before using the formula, arrange the equation in:": "",
  "Standard form: ax² + bx + c = 0": "",
  "What is the discriminant in the quadratic formula?": "",
  "b² − 4ac — the expression under the square root": "",
  "If the discriminant is negative, the equation has:": "",
  "No real solutions (two complex solutions)": ""
}